A logistic regression model was evaluated using 5-fold cross-validation, achieving an average accuracy of about 97%. This indicates that service-related variables (such as computers, books, and front desk services) are very strong predictors of high satisfaction. The consistent performance across folds shows the model is stable and reliable, not dependent on a single train/test split.

8. Expected Value
The model was evaluated using an expected value framework rather than accuracy alone. Since the goal is to identify dissatisfied students, false negatives (failing to detect unhappy students) carry a higher cost than false positives (unnecessary outreach). Therefore, the best model is one that minimizes false negatives, even at the expense of slightly more false positives. The logistic regression model performed well, with high accuracy and likely low false negatives, indicating a high expected value. However, model selection should prioritize reducing missed dissatisfied students rather than maximizing accuracy alone.

